Problem  Prove by induction that the $i$th Fibonacci number satisfies the equality egin{equation}  F_i=  rac{\phi^i-\hat{\phi}^i}{\sqrt{5}},\end{equation}where $\phi$ is the golden ratio and $\hat{\phi}$​ is its conjugate.(two roots of the equation） egin{equation}  x^2 = x + 1\end{equation}Proof      Base case:    For $i=0,$ egin{equation} egin{aligned} rac{\phi^0-\hat{\phi}^0}{\sqrt{5}} &amp;=  rac{1-1}{\sqrt{5}} 
ewline   &amp;= 0 
ewline   &amp;= F_0.\end{aligned}\end{equation}    For $i=1,$ egin{aligned} rac{\phi^1-\hat{\phi}^1}{\sqrt{5}} &amp;=  rac{(1+\sqrt{5})-(1-\sqrt{5})}{2\sqrt{5}} 
ewline   &amp;= 1 
ewline   &amp;= F_1.\end{aligned}        Induction step: Suppose $i=k,$                  $F_k =  rac{\phi^k-\hat{\phi}^k}{\sqrt{5}},	ag{1}$                    $F_{k-1} =  rac{\phi^{k-1}-\hat{\phi}^{k-1}}{\sqrt{5}}and	ag{3}$                    $F_{k+1} =  rac{\phi^{k+1}-\hat{\phi}^{k+1}}{\sqrt{5}}	ag{2}$               egin{aligned}F_{k-1} + F_{k} &amp;=  rac{\phi^{k-1}-\hat{\phi}^{k-1}}{\sqrt{5}} +  rac{\phi^{k}-\hat{\phi}^{k}}{\sqrt{5}} 
ewline   &amp;=  rac{\phi^{k-1}(1+\phi) - \hat{\phi}^{k-1}(1+\hat{\phi})}{\sqrt{5}}\end{aligned}    Because $\phi$ and $\hat{\phi}$ are two roots of $ x^2 = x + 1$, above equation can be written as     egin{aligned} rac{\phi^{k-1} \cdot \phi^2 - \hat{\phi}^{k-1} \cdot \hat{\phi}^2}{\sqrt{5}} &amp;=  rac{\phi^{k+1} - \hat{\phi}^{k+1}}{\sqrt{5}} 
ewline  &amp;= F_{k+1}. \end{aligned}  $ lacksquare$References  Proof-by-induction
